Growing up, Michael Burry obsessively studied investing.

As he read more and more about the topic, naturally, he came across the richest investor in the world, Warren Buffett.

And after he read everything there is to read about Buffett‚Äôs success, Burry was certain of 1 thing:

‚ÄúIf you are going to be a great investor,‚Äù Burry said, ‚Äúyou have to fit the style to who you are.‚Äù

‚ÄúAt one point I recognized that Warren Buffett, though he had every advantage in learning from Ben Graham, did not copy Ben Graham, but rather set out on his own path, and ran money his way, by his own rules.‚Äù

Takeaway 1:

To Burry, the big lesson from Buffett's success is that investors should match their style to their unique personality traits.

This is known in economics as ‚Äúmatch quality‚Äù‚Äîthe degree of alignment between the traits of a profession and the traits of a person.

When the musicians John Mayer and Cory Wong got together to play guitar, Mayer identified Wong as someone who has perfectly fit his playing style to his physical and mental traits.

Mayer said he had watched a bunch of videos of Wong playing guitar, and as he did, he watched Wong‚Äôs right hand‚Äîhis strumming hand.

‚ÄúYou have an anatomy thing working for you with your right hand,‚Äù Mayer said. ‚ÄúYour right hand is shaped in a way‚Äîyou have long fingers, very sinewy hands‚Äîthat allows you to play like that.‚Äù

Wong‚Äôs anatomy and his playing style are completely aligned, Mayer says.

‚ÄúAnd I wish more players would embrace finding their strengths are anatomically‚Äîthe way your hand is shaped, the way your mind works, etc.‚Äîand play to those strengths.‚Äù

Takeaway 2:

Buffett studied the greats that came before him, but he didn‚Äôt copy them. Instead, as Burry said, he took what he learned to form his own style.

This strategy works beyond just the world of investing.

It's said, for instance, that the filmmaker Quentin Tarantino knows so much about his filmmaking heroes that he could write their biographies.

‚ÄúWhether it be Brian de Palma or Howard Marks or Douglas Sirk or Scorcese,‚Äù Tarantino explains, ‚ÄúI would just obsess about filmmakers the way a baseball fan might obsess about their favorite baseball players.‚Äù

And yet, Tarantino movies are distinctly Tarantino‚Äîhe set out on his own path, and made Movies his way, by his own rules.

- - -

‚ÄúOne of the most critical factors in becoming a high performer is the degree to which your relationship to your pursuit stays in harmony with your unique disposition.‚Äù ‚Äî Josh Waitzkin

Follow @bpoppenheimer for more content like this!

Gross domestic income, a measure of total economic activity, shrank in both the fourth quarter and the first quarter. Two negative quarters of output growth are one indicator of a recession.

Labor productivity fell 2.1% in the first quarter from the fourth at an annual rate, and was down 0.8% in the first quarter from a year earlier, the Labor Department said. That is the fifth-straight quarter of negative year-over-year productivity growth‚Äîthe longest such run since records began in 1948

‚ÄúOver the past two quarters, real GDP shows the economy expanding by 1.0%, not far off potential growth, whereas GDI shows it contracting by 1.4%, which amounts to a decent-sized recession,‚Äù said Paul Ashworth, chief U.S. economist at Capital Economics.

The second quarter is also shaping up to be weak. S&P Global Market Intelligence sees second-quarter real GDP expanding at a 0.8% annual rate; Morgan Stanley projects 0.3%. The Atlanta Fed‚Äôs GDPNow model estimates 2%.

GDI measures incomes earned in wages and profits, while GDP tallies up purchases of goods and services produced.

JPMorgan‚Äôs Michele Sees Bonds Approaching ‚ÄòDouble Digit‚Äô Returns

Wall Street veteran Bob Michele is eyeing opportunities in intermediate government bonds and investment grade credit as the US edges toward a recession by the end of the year.

‚ÄúThis is the time where you clip coupons because yields have reset materially higher from where they were at the end of 2021,‚Äù Michele told Bloomberg Television on Wednesday. ‚ÄúActually, when you look at real yields in the bond market, they‚Äôre the highest level going back 15, 17 years. We‚Äôre going to get some capital appreciation on top of the coupon clipping. I‚Äôm looking for close to double-digit returns on the Bloomberg aggregate over the next year.‚Äù

The chief investment officer for JPMorgan Investment Management Inc. said he sees opportunities in five-year Treasuries, given the ‚Äúbackup in yields.‚Äù He added that yields in the US investment-grade corporate bond market have once again attracted overseas investors.

Michele reiterated his call to see 3% across the yield curve, which would represent a victory over inflation but a loss for the US economy. He warned against this cycle‚Äôs ‚Äúcash trap‚Äù effect.

‚ÄúYou put money there and then a year from now it‚Äôs gone. Your cash run rate is probably below 4% a year from now. So you‚Äôve lost all of that, and then the yield curve starts to adjust to a central bank that‚Äôs cutting rates again,‚Äù he said.

üá∫üá∏üá∫üá¶‚ö°Ô∏è In February 2023, Zelensky met with the leadership of JP Morgan, one of the largest investment banks in the world. They discussed investments in the "recovery" of Ukraine.

As with the BlackRock fund, JP Morgan's activities in Ukraine are an effective scheme for appropriating state assets and exploiting them in the interests of Western states.

Back in 2019, JP Morgan directly loaned the cash-strapped Ukrainian government about $350 million by purchasing the country's Eurobonds. 

Now the discussion revolves around the creation of an investment platform, which implies much larger investment volumes.

It's worth noting that the bonds are backed by state assets, which include infrastructure facilities, thermal power plants, nuclear power plants, agricultural and industrial enterprises.

Given the current state of the Ukrainian economy, it is impossible to repay the Ukrainian Eurobonds, and this is being exploited by major investors like JP Morgan. 

If the Ukrainian government defaults on the Eurobonds, the state assets will be transferred to the ownership of the bank. This is a highly probable scenario since Ukraine's budget deficit is currently covered by IMF funds.

At the same time, the US private investment management company Vanguard Group is acquiring Ukrainian state assets under the guise of economic assistance to the Kiev regime.

In late April 2023, news began to emerge that the Ukrainian state company for oil and natural gas extraction, transportation, and processing, "Naftogaz," was in negotiations with foreign giants Chevron, ExxonMobil, and Halliburton regarding the sale of its assets.

According to the chairman of Naftogaz, Alexei Chernyshov, this will allow for increased extraction of energy resources and contribute to the replacement of Russian supplies to Europe in the coming years. 

However, he failed to mention that, as a result, control over the entire oil and gas sector of Ukraine will fall into the hands of these companies.

Despite the appearance of competition, Chevron, ExxonMobil, and Halliburton are united by the financial company Vanguard, which holds the most shares in the three companies and effectively controls and directs their activities.
